Let the radius of the smaller circle be $r$ and the radius of the larger circle be $R$. Let $O$ be the center of the circles. 

[asy]
size(100);
pair O=(0,0), P=(0,1), A=(-0.7,0.7), B=(0.7,0.7);
draw(circle(O,1));
draw(circle(P,0.3));
draw(P--A--O--cycle);
draw(P--B--O);
draw(arc(P,0.3,135,180));
draw(arc(O,1,144,180));
label("$O$",O,SW);
label("$P$",P,N);
label("$r$",P--O,SE);
label("$R$",O--B,NE);
label("$\theta$",O+(0.1,0.05),NE);
label("$\theta$",P+(0.1,0.05),NE);
[/asy]

Let $\theta$ be the measure of the 45 degree angle at $P$. Then the length of the arc on the smaller circle is $\theta r$. 

Let $\alpha$ be the measure of the 36 degree angle at $P$. Then the length of the arc on the larger circle is $\alpha R$. 

Since the two arcs have the same length, we have $\theta r = \alpha R$. 

We also know that $\theta = 2\alpha$, since the 45 degree angle is twice the 36 degree angle. 

Substituting $\theta = 2\alpha$ into $\theta r = \alpha R$, we get $2\alpha r = \alpha R$, which simplifies to $R = 2r$. 

The ratio of the areas of the two circles is $\left(\frac{r}{R}\right)^2 = \left(\frac{r}{2r}\right)^2 = \boxed{\frac{1}{4}}$. 

So the answer is $\boxed{\frac{1}{4}}$.

